fields.name: Field Separator
fields.text: This field contains the separator between the segment ID and the first real field, MSH-2-encoding characters. As such it serves as the separator and defines the character to be used as a separator for the rest of the message.

fields.name: Encoding Characters
fields.text: This field contains the four characters in the following order: the component separator, repetition separator, escape character, and subcomponent separator.

fields.name: Sending Application
fields.text: This field uniquely identifies the application sending the message. The value is locally defined and often assigned by the IIS. This is not the product, but rather the name of the specific instance. For instance, the IIS in Georgia (GRITS) is an instance based on the Wisconsin IIS (WIR). The code for GRITS would be specific to GRITS.

fields.name: Sending Facility
fields.text:
This field identifies the organization responsible for the operations of the sending application. Locally defined codes accommodate local needs. The first component shall be the name space ID found in User-defined Table 0362. The second and third components are reserved for use of OIDs.

Depending on the architecture of the integration, MSH-4 may or may not be the same organization that is responsible for the content of the message. For example, if an EHR communicates with an IIS via a Health Information Exchange (HIE), the value in MSH-4 may change (depending on local policy) from representing the EHR to representing the HIE as the message moves between systems. This value may represent the same organization as sent in MSH-22 but does not have to.

fields.name: Receiving Application
fields.text: This field uniquely identifies the application sending the message. The value is locally defined and often assigned by the IIS. This is not the product, but rather the name of the specific instance. For instance, the IIS in Georgia (GRITS) is an instance based on the Wisconsin IIS (WIR). The code for GRITS would be specific to GRITS.

fields.name: Receiving Facility
fields.text:
This field identifies the organization responsible for the operations of the receiving application. Locally defined codes will accommodate local needs.

Depending on the architecture of the integration, MSH-6 may or may not be the same organization that is the ultimate recipient of the message. For example, if an EHR communicates with an IIS via a Health Information Exchange (HIE), the value in MSH-6 may change (depending on local policy) from representing the HIE to representing the IIS as the message moves between systems. This value may represent the same organization as sent in MSH-23 but does not have to.

fields.name: Date/Time of Message
fields.text: This field contains the date/time that the sending system created the message.

fields.name: Message Type
fields.text: This field contains the message type, trigger event, and the message structure ID for the message.

fields.name: Message Control ID
fields.text: This field contains the identifier assigned by the sending system that uniquely identifies a message instance. This identifier is unique within the scope of the sending system and the YYYYMMDD portion of message date (MSH-7). The receiving system echoes this ID back to the sending system in the Message Acknowledgment segment (MSA). The content and format of the data sent in this field is the responsibility of the sender.

fields.name: Processing ID
fields.text: This field is used to decide whether to process the message as defined in HL7 Application (level 7) Processing rules.

fields.name: Version ID
fields.text: This field contains the identifier of the version of the HL7 messaging standard used in constructing, interpreting and validating the message.

fields.name: Accept Acknowledgment Type
fields.text:
This field identifies the conditions under which accept acknowledgments are required to be returned in response to this message. 

The accept acknowledgement indicates if the message was safely received or not. It does not indicate successful processing. The application acknowledgement indicates the outcome of processing.

fields.name: Application Acknowledgment Type
fields.text: This field contains the conditions under which application acknowledgments are required to be returned in response to this message.

fields.name: Message Profile Identifier
fields.text: Sites use this field to assert adherence to, or reference, a message profile. Message profiles contain detailed explanations of grammar, syntax, and usage for a particular message or set of messages.

fields.name: Sending Responsible Organization
fields.text:
Business organization that originated and is accountable for the content of the message.

Currently, MSH provides fields to transmit both sending/receiving applications and facilities (MSH-3 through MSH-6). However, these levels of organization do not necessarily relate to or imply a legal entity such as a business organization. As such, multiple legal entities (organizations) may share a service bureau, with the same application and facility identifiers. Another level of detail is required to delineate the various organizations using the same service bureau.

Therefore, the Sending Responsible Organization field provides a complete picture from the application level to the overall business level. The Business Organization represents the legal entity responsible for the contents of the message.

fields.name: Receiving Responsible Organization
fields.text:
Business organization that is the intended receiver of the message and is accountable for acting on the data conveyed by the transaction.

This field has the same justification as the Sending Responsible Organization except in the role of the Receiving Responsible Organization.  The receiving organization has the legal responsibility to act on the information in the message.

fields.name: Date/Time of Birth
fields.text:
This field contains the patient's date and time of birth. Only the date is required.

Date of Birth is generally considered to be independent of the time zone. If a time is available, the interacting systems should not convert the patient's accepted date of birth to a local equivalent.

fields.text: When a patient was part of a multiple birth, a value (number) indicating the patient's birth order is sent in this field.

fields.name: Patient Death Date and Time
fields.text:
This field contains the date and time at which the patient death occurred.

Date of Death is generally considered to be independent of the time zone. If a time is available, the sending and receiving systems should not convert the patient's accepted date of death to a local equivalent.

fields.name: Patient Death Indicator
fields.text:
This field indicates whether the patient is deceased. 

Y -  the patient is deceased

N - the patient is not deceased

Empty - death status is undetermined

It is not the Primary Care Practitioner or Medical Home. The meaning of this field should not be expanded to include the concept of medical home.

fields.text: This field contains a user-defined code indicating what level of publicity is allowed for the patient. In the context of immunization messages, this refers to how a person wishes to be contacted in a reminder or recall situation

fields.name: Protection Indicator
fields.text:
This field identifies whether a person's information may be shared with others (local policies determine how data are protected). The protection state must be explicitly captured in the system documenting the immunization. If it is not actively determined, then the protection indicator shall be empty.

There are 3 states:

Protection State
Code
Yes, protect the data. Patient (or guardian) has indicated that the information shall be protected. (Do not share data)
Y
No, it is not necessary to protect data from other clinicians. Patient (or guardian) has indicated that the information does not need to be protected. (Sharing is OK)
N
No determination has been made regarding patient's (or guardian's) wishes regarding information sharing
PD1-12 is empty


Notes on use of Y for Protection Indicator in starting in version 2.5.1 Guides

Note that Implementation Guides based on HL7 versions less than 2.5 stated that Y meant that a person's information could be shared. This was an incorrect interpretation of the use of this field. The meaning now aligns with the base definition of HL7, that is, Y means data must be protected. Existing systems that use the old meaning will need to determine how they will send the correct value in messages based on version 2.5.1 or beyond. 

 Note that the value sent in a message that is based on the 2.3.1 or 2.4 version of the HL7 standard shall continue to follow the old guidance. That is, Y means sharing is allowed and N means sharing is not allowed. A system receiving a message containing a PD1 segment must process the protection indicator in a way consistent with the HL7 version the message is based on.

fields.name: Protection Indicator Effective Date
fields.text: This field indicates the effective date for PD1-12 - Protection Indicator.

fields.name: Immunization Registry Status
fields.text:
This field identifies the current status of the patient in relation to the sending organization.

This field captures whether the sending organization considers this an active patient. There are several classes of responsibility. The status may be different between the sending and receiving systems.  For instance, a person may no longer be active with a provider organization, but may still be active in the public health jurisdiction, which has the Immunization Information System (IIS). In this case the provider organization would indicate that the person was inactive in their system using this field in a message from them. The IIS would indicate that person was active in a message from the IIS.

The term "sending provider organization" refers to the organization that is accountable for the content of the message. This may be an EHR for a VXU^V04 message or an IIS for an RSP^K11 message. PD1-16 should reflect the status of the patient relative to the system creating the message.

fields.name: Immunization Registry Status Effective Date
fields.text: This field indicates the effective date for the registry status reported in PD1-16 - Immunization Registry Status.

fields.name: Publicity Code Effective Date
fields.text: This is the effective date for PD1-11 - Publicity Code.

name: PD1
text1: The Patient Demographic Segment contains patient demographic information that may change from time to time. There are three primary uses for PD1 in Immunization Messages. These include indicating whether the person wants his/her data protected, whether the person wants to receive recall/reminder notices and the person's current status in the system generating the message.

label: RXA_IZ_01

fields.name: Give Sub-ID Counter
fields.comment: Note that in the Conformance Statement,  “0” is zero.
fields.text: This field is used to match an RXA and RXG, which is not applicable to this document.

fields.name: Administration Sub-ID Counter
fields.text: This field is used to track multiple RXA segments under an ORC. Since each ORC has only one RXA in immunization messages, this field is constrained to 1. This should not be used for indicating dose number, which is messaged via the OBX segment.

fields.name: Date/Time Start of Administration
fields.text: The date this vaccination occurred. In the case of refusal or deferral, this is the date that the refusal or deferral was recorded.

fields.name: Date/Time End of Administration
fields.text: This field is specified as required in the HL7 standard. An immunization is given at a point in time, and in the context of immunization, the End date/time is equivalent to the Start date/time. For this reason, this document has required this to be equal to RXA-3.

fields.name: Administered Code
fields.comment: Support for CVX and NDC codes are strongly preferred.
fields.text: This field identifies the medical substance administered. If the substance administered is a vaccine, CVX and NDC codes are used for historical and new administrations respectively. The second set of three components may be used to represent the same vaccine using a different coding system.

fields.name: Administered Amount
fields.text: This field records the amount of pharmaceutical administered. The units are expressed in the next field, RXA-7. When the administered amount is unknown, this field should be populated with the value "999".

fields.name: Administered Units
fields.text: This field is conditional because it is required if the administered amount code does not imply units. This field must be in simple units that reflect the actual quantity of the substance administered. It does not include compound units. This field is not required if RXA-6 is populated with 999.

fields.name: Administration Notes
fields.comment: The primary use of this field is to convey if this immunization record is based on a historical record or was given by the provider recording the immunization. All systems should be able to support this use. Other uses of this field are permitted, but must be agreed upon locally.
fields.text: This field is used to indicate whether this immunization record is based on a historical record or was given by the reporting provider. It should contain the information source.

fields.name: Administering Provider
fields.comment: This is the person who gave the administration or the vaccinator. It is not the ordering clinician.
fields.text: This field is intended to contain the name and provider ID of the person physically administering the pharmaceutical.

fields.name: Administered-at Location
fields.comment: RXA-11 has been replaced by RXA-27.

fields.name: Substance Lot Number
fields.text: This field contains the lot number of the medical substance administered. It may remain empty if the dose is from a historical record.

fields.name: Substance Expiration Date
fields.text:
This field contains the expiration date of the medical substance administered. It may remain empty if the dose is from a historical record.

Note: Vaccine expiration date does not always have a "day" component; therefore, such a date may be transmitted as YYYYMM.

fields.name: Substance Manufacturer Name
fields.text: This field contains the manufacturer of the medical substance administered.

fields.name: Substance/Treatment Refusal Reason
fields.text: This field contains the reason the patient refused the medical substance/treatment. Any entry in the field indicates that the patient did not take the substance.

fields.name: Completion Status
fields.text: Status of treatment administration event.

fields.name: Action Code - RXA
fields.text:
This field indicates the action expected by the system constructing the message. It can facilitate update or deletion of immunization records.

When processing Update or Delete messages, ORC-3, Placer order number, may be used to link to a specific immunization if the system receiving the message has recorded this from the initial order. Local implementers should specify its use in a local implementation guide.

The action code U (Update) is used to indicate to a receiver that a previously sent immunization should be changed. Most IIS have specific criteria for determining whether to add or update an immunization that do not rely directly on this field. 

When sending a Delete message, the VXU^V04 message should be constructed such that all data in the message, including segments in the Order Group, is the same as the most recent message for the administration, except for the Action Code (RXA-21) which should be D. Importantly, the filler ID in ORC-3 should be the same between messages as this ID may be crucial to identifying the correct administration to remove. Once the inaccurate data has been deleted, additional independent messages (adds, refusals, etc) can be sent to accurately populate the receiving system.

fields.name: Administer-at
fields.text: This field specifies the location where the drug or treatment was administered.

Support for CVX and NDC codes are strongly preferred.

name: RXA
text1: The RXA segment carries pharmacy administration data. It is paired with the ORC segment within the Order Group of segments. Because the Order Group is allowed to repeat, an unlimited numbers of vaccinations may be included in a message. Each RXA must be preceded by an ORC.

predicates.description: If the occurrence of RXA-9 using the NIP001 coding system is valued "00" and RXA-20 is valued "CP" or "PA"

conformanceStatements.description: The value of ORC-1(Order Control) SHALL be 'RE'.
If RXA-20 (Completion Status) is valued “NA” or “RE” then ORC-3.1 SHALL be valued “9999”.

label: ORC_IZ_01

fields.name: Order Control
fields.text: Determines the function of the order segment.

fields.name: Placer Order Number
fields.text:
The placer order number is used to uniquely identify this order among all orders sent by a provider organization.

In the case where the ordering provider organization is not known, this field may be left empty.

fields.name: Filler Order Number
fields.text:
The filler order number is used to uniquely identify this order among all orders sent by a provider organization that filled the order. 

Use of this foreign key will allow the system receiving the message to accurately identify the previously sent immunization record, facilitating update or deletion of that record.

In the case where a historic immunization is being recorded (i.e. from an immunization card), the system reporting the administration SHALL assign an identifier as if it were an immunization administered by a provider associated with the provider organization owning the system.

Note that the receiving system will need to store this value in addition to its own internal ID in order for this to be used.

fields.name: Entered By
fields.text: This identifies the individual that entered this particular order.

fields.name: Ordering Provider
fields.text: This field contains the identity of the person who is responsible for creating the request (i.e., ordering physician). In the case where this segment is associated with a historic immunization record and the ordering provider is not known, then this field should not be populated.

fields.name: Entering Organization
fields.text: This field identifies the organization that the enterer belonged to at the time he/she enters/maintains the order, such as medical group or department. The person who entered the request is defined in ORC-10 (entered by).

name: ORC
text1: The Common Order segment (ORC) is used to transmit fields that are common to all orders (all types of services that are requested). While not all immunizations transmitted in an immunization message are able to be associated with an order, each RXA must be associated with one ORC, per the HL7 base standard.

label: RXR_IZ

fields.name: Route
fields.text: This field is the route of administration.

fields.name: Administration Site
fields.text: This field contains the site of the administration route.

name: RXR
text1: The Pharmacy/Treatment Route segment contains the combination of route and site that are prescribed as they apply to a particular order.

If the value of OBX-2(Value Type) is 'NM'.

The value of OBX-11(Observation Result Status) SHALL be 'F'.
The value of OBX-4.1 (Observation SubID) SHALL be a positive integer.

label: OBX_IZ_01

fields.name: Set ID - OBX
fields.text: This field contains the sequence number. The first instance may be set to 1 and each subsequent instance may be the next number in sequence. Numbering might not be restarted within a message. That is, if a message had 3 order groups and each had 3 OBX, the last OBX in the message would have value of 9 for this field. Alternatively, the Set ID is also allowed to restart within a message, between order groups. That is, if a message had 3 order groups and each had 3 OBX segments, all three order groups would contain OBX segments with Set IDs of 1, 2 and 3. Either approach, restarting or not restarting per order group, is allowed.

fields.name: Value Type
fields.text: This field contains the format of the observation value in OBX-5.

fields.name: Observation Identifier
fields.comment: This indicates what this observation refers to. It poses the question that is answered by OBX-5.
fields.text:
This field contains a unique identifier for the observation. 

This may be thought of as a question that the observation in OBX-5 answers. In the example above, the question is "what funding program was this person eligible for when this vaccine was administered". The answer in OBX-5 could be "VFC eligible - MEDICAID".

 LOINC shall be the standard coding system for this field if an appropriate LOINC code exists. If a local coding system is in use, a local code should also be sent to help with identification of coding issues. When no valid LOINC exists the local code may be the only code sent. When populating this field with values, this guide does not give preference to the triplet in which the standard (LOINC) code should appear.

fields.name: Observation Sub-ID
fields.text:
This field is used to group related observations by setting the value to the same number. For example, recording VIS fully-encoded text string and VIS presentation date for a combination vaccination requires multiple OBX segment groups. One OBX would indicate the document type and version using the fully-encoded text string. It would have an associated OBX indicating the VIS presentation date. These would have the same OBX-4 value to allow them to be linked. The second set of related OBX segments for the next vaccine component would have another OBX-4 value common to each of them.

The observation Sub-ID must be unique for each related set of observations under a given vaccine order group. Sub-IDs may be re-used between order groups in the message.

fields.name: Observation Value
fields.comment: This is the observation value and answers the question posed by OBX-3.
fields.text: This field contains the value of the observation being reported. OBX-2 (Value Type) defines the data type for this field.  OBX -3 (Observation Identifier) defines the concept being reported in this field.

fields.name: Units
fields.text:
This shall be the units for the value in OBX-5.

If there is not a unit of measure available while the Condition Predicated is true, then the value "NA" may be used in OBX-6.1 and "HL70353" in OBX-6.3.

fields.name: Observation Result Status
fields.text: This field contains the observation result status.

fields.name: Date/Time of the Observation
fields.text: This field records the time of the observation.

name: OBX
text1:
The observation result segment has many uses. It carries observations about the object of its parent segment. In this document it is associated with the RXA segment. The basic format is a question (OBX-3) and an answer (OBX-5).

The Co-Constraints table at the end of this section specifies how to populate an OBX segment based on the observation being messaged. To use the table, find the row containing the LOINC code being messaged in OBX-3. Then use the remaining columns to determine how to populate the remainder of the segment.The data type for OBX-2 is indicated along with valid value sets for various fields (when appropriate for the date type), including OBX-5. When populating the segment, the value in OBX-2 must correspond to a value found in HL7 table 0125 but the format of the data in OBX-5 should correspond to a data type flavor described in this document and identified in the "Comments" column. For example, when sending a coded observation value, OBX-2 should be the value "CWE" but OBX-5 should be formatted according to the requirements of the CWE_01 data type flavor.

field.name: Observation Identifier
field.comment: This indicates what this observation refers to. It poses the question that is answered by OBX-5.
field.text:
This field contains a unique identifier for the observation. 

This may be thought of as a question that the observation in OBX-5 answers. In the example above, the question is "what funding program was this person eligible for when this vaccine was administered". The answer in OBX-5 could be "VFC eligible - MEDICAID".

 LOINC shall be the standard coding system for this field if an appropriate LOINC code exists. If a local coding system is in use, a local code should also be sent to help with identification of coding issues. When no valid LOINC exists the local code may be the only code sent.

field.name: Value Type
field.text: This field contains the format of the observation value in OBX-5.

field.name: Observation Value
field.comment: This is the observation value and answers the question posed by OBX-3.
field.text:
This field contains the value observed by the observation producer. OBX-2-value type contains the data type for this field according to which observation value is formatted.

This field contains the value of OBX-3-observation identifier of the same segment. Depending upon the observation, the data type may be a number (e.g., dose number), a coded answer (e.g., a vaccine), or a date/time (the date/time that the VIS was given to the client/parent). An observation value is always represented as the data type specified in OBX-2-value type of the same segment. Whether numeric or short text, the answer shall be recorded in ASCII text.

fields.name: Set ID - OBX
fields.text: This field contains the sequence number. The first instance may be set to 1 and each subsequent instance may be the next number in sequence. Numbering might not be restarted within a message. That is, if a message had 3 order groups and each had 3 OBX, the last OBX in the message would have value of 9 for this field. Alternatively, the Set ID is also allowed to restart within a message, between order groups. This is, if a message had 3 order groups and each had 3 OBX segments, all three order groups would contain OBX segments with Set IDs of 1, 2 and 3. Either approach, restarting or not restarting per order group, is allowed.

fields.name: Observation Sub-ID
fields.text:
This field is used to group related observations by setting the value to the same number. For example, recording VIS fully-encoded text string and VIS presentation date for a combination vaccination requires multiple OBX segment groups. One OBX would indicate the document type and version using the fully-encoded text string. It would have an associated OBX indicating the VIS presentation date. These would have the same OBX-4 value to allow them to be linked. The second set of related OBX segments for the next vaccine component would have another OBX-4 value common to each of them.

The observation Sub-ID must be unique for each related set of observations under a given vaccine order group. Sub-IDs may be re-used between order groups in the message.

fields.name: Set ID - OBX
fields.text: This field contains the sequence number. The first instance may be set to 1 and each subsequent instance may be the next number in sequence. Numbering might not be restarted within a message. That is, if a message had 3 order groups and each had 3 OBX, the last OBX in the message would have value of 9 for this field. Alternatively, the Set ID is also allowed to restart within a message, between order groups. This is, if a message had 3 order groups and each had 3 OBX segments, all three order groups would contain OBX segments with Set IDs of 1, 2 and 3. Either approach, restarting or not restarting per order group, is allowed.

fields.text:
This field contains a unique identifier for the observation. 

This may be thought of as a question that the observation in OBX-5 answers. In the example above, the question is "what funding program was this person eligible for when this vaccine was administered". The answer in OBX-5 could be "VFC eligible - MEDICAID".

 LOINC shall be the standard coding system for this field if an appropriate LOINC code exists. If a local coding system is in use, a local code should also be sent to help with identification of coding issues. When no valid LOINC exists the local code may be the only code sent. When populating this field with values, this guide does not give preference to the triplet in which the standard (LOINC) code should appear.

fields.name: Observation Sub-ID
fields.text:
This field is used to group related observations by setting the value to the same number. For example, recording VIS fully-encoded text string and VIS presentation date for a combination vaccination requires multiple OBX segment groups. One OBX would indicate the document type and version using the fully-encoded text string. It would have an associated OBX indicating the VIS presentation date. These would have the same OBX-4 value to allow them to be linked. The second set of related OBX segments for the next vaccine component would have another OBX-4 value common to each of them.

The observation Sub-ID must be unique for each related set of observations under a given vaccine order group. Sub-IDs may be re-used between order groups in the message.

name: OBX
text1:
The observation result segment has many uses. It carries observations about the object of its parent segment. In this document it is associated with the RXA segment. The basic format is a question (OBX-3) and an answer (OBX-5).

The Co-Constraints table at the end of this section specifies how to populate an OBX segment based on the observation being messaged. To use the table, find the row containing the LOINC code being messaged in OBX-3. Then use the remaining columns to determine how to populate the remainder of the segment. The data type for OBX-2 is indicated along with valid value sets for various fields (when appropriate for the date type), including OBX-5. When populating the segment, the value in OBX-2 must correspond to a value found in HL7 table 0125 but the format of the data in OBX-5 should correspond to a data type flavor described in this document and identified in the "Comments" column. For example, when sending a coded observation value, OBX-2 should be the value "CWE" but OBX-5 should be formatted according to the requirements of the CWE_01 data type flavor.

label: ORC_IZ_02

fields.name: Order Control
fields.text: Determines the function of the order segment.

fields.name: Placer Order Number
fields.text:
The placer order number is used to uniquely identify this order among all orders sent by a provider organization.

In the case where the ordering provider organization is not known, this field may be left empty.

fields.name: Filler Order Number
fields.text:
The filler order number is used to uniquely identify this order among all orders sent by a provider organization that filled the order. 

Use of this foreign key will allow the system receiving the message to accurately identify the previously sent immunization record, facilitating update or deletion of that record.

In the case where a historic immunization is being recorded (i.e. from an immunization card), the system reporting the administration SHALL assign an identifier as if it were an immunization administered by a provider associated with the provider organization owning the system.

Note that the receiving system will need to store this value in addition to its own internal ID in order for this to be used.

fields.name: Entering Organization
fields.text: This field identifies the organization that the enterer belonged to at the time he/she enters/maintains the order, such as medical group or department. The person who entered the request is defined in ORC-10 (entered by).

name: ORC
text1: The Common Order segment (ORC) is used to transmit fields that are common to all orders (all types of services that are requested). While not all immunizations transmitted in an immunization message are able to be associated with an order, each RXA must be associated with one ORC, per the HL7 base standard.

label: PID_IZ_02

fields.name: Set ID - PID
fields.text: This field contains the number that identifies this transaction.

fields.name: Patient Identifier List
fields.text: This field contains the list of identifiers (one or more) used by the healthcare facility to uniquely identify a patient (e.g., medical record number, billing number, birth registry, national unique individual identifier, etc.).

fields.name: Patient Name
fields.text: This field contains the name(s) of the patient

fields.name: Mother's Maiden Name
fields.text: This field contains the family name under which the mother was born (i.e., before marriage). It is used to distinguish between patients with similar demographics.

fields.name: Date/Time of Birth
fields.text:
This field contains the patient's date and time of birth. Only the date is required.

Date of Birth is generally considered to be independent of the time zone. If a time is available, the interacting systems should not convert the patient's accepted date of birth to a local equivalent.

fields.name: Administrative Sex
fields.text: This field contains the patient's sex.

fields.name: Patient Address
fields.text: This field contains the mailing address of the patient.

fields.name: Primary Language
fields.comment:
ISO 639 shall be used for Language. It is available from PHIN-VADS at:
http://phinvads.cdc.gov/vads/ViewValueSet.action?id=43D34BBC-617F-DD11-B38D-00188B398520#
The code used from HL70396 table is ISO6392.

fields.name: Birth Order
fields.comment: This field contains a number indicating the person’s birth order within a single pregnancy. 1 for the first child born and 2 for the second, etc.

fields.name: Patient Death Indicator
fields.text:
This field indicates whether the patient is deceased. 

Y -  the patient is deceased

N - the patient is not deceased

Empty - death status is undetermined

This field may be considered for use  by trading partners.

label: RXA_IZ_02

fields.name: Give Sub-ID Counter
fields.comment: Note that in the Conformance Statement,  “0” is zero.
fields.text: This field is used to match an RXA and RXG, which is not applicable to this document.

fields.name: Administration Sub-ID Counter
fields.text: This field is used to track multiple RXA segments under an ORC. Since each ORC has only one RXA in immunization messages, this field is constrained to 1. This should not be used for indicating dose number, which is messaged via the OBX segment.

fields.name: Date/Time Start of Administration
fields.text: The date this vaccination occurred. In the case of refusal or deferral, this is the date that the refusal or deferral was recorded. In the case of a forecast dose, this is the date the forecast was made.

fields.name: Date/Time End of Administration
fields.text: This field is specified as required in the HL7 standard. An immunization is given at a point in time, and in the context of immunization, the End date/time is equivalent to the Start date/time. For this reason, this document has required this to be equal to RXA-3.

fields.name: Administered Code
fields.comment: Support for CVX codes is strongly preferred.
fields.text: This field identifies the medical substance administered.

fields.name: Administered Amount
fields.text: This field records the amount of pharmaceutical administered. The units are expressed in the next field, RXA-7. When the administered amount is unknown, this field should be populated with the value "999".

fields.name: Administered Units
fields.text: This field is conditional because it is required if the administered amount code does not imply units. This field must be in simple units that reflect the actual quantity of the substance administered. It does not include compound units. This field is not required if RXA-6 is populated with 999.

fields.name: Administration Notes
fields.comment: The primary use of this field is to convey if this immunization record is based on a historical record or was given by the provider recording the immunization. All systems should be able to support this use. Other uses of this field are permitted, but must be agreed upon locally.
fields.text: This field is used to indicate whether this immunization record is based on a historical record or was given by the reporting provider. It should contain the information source.

fields.name: Administering Provider
fields.comment: This is the person who gave the administration or the vaccinator. It is not the ordering clinician.
fields.text: This field is intended to contain the name and provider ID of the person physically administering the pharmaceutical.

fields.name: Administered-at Location
fields.comment: RXA-11 has been replaced by RXA-27.

fields.name: Substance Lot Number
fields.text: This field contains the lot number of the medical substance administered. It may remain empty if the dose is from a historical record.

fields.name: Substance Expiration Date
fields.text:
This field contains the expiration date of the medical substance administered. It may remain empty if the dose is from a historical record.

Note: Vaccine expiration date does not always have a "day" component; therefore, such a date may be transmitted as YYYYMM.

fields.name: Substance Manufacturer Name
fields.text: This field contains the manufacturer of the medical substance administered.

fields.name: Substance/Treatment Refusal Reason
fields.text: This field contains the reason the patient refused the medical substance/treatment. Any entry in the field indicates that the patient did not take the substance.

fields.name: Completion Status
fields.text: Status of treatment administration event.

fields.name: Administer-at
fields.text: This field specifies the location where the drug or treatment was administered.

name: RXA
text1: The RXA segment carries pharmacy administration data. It is paired with the ORC segment within the Order Group of segments. Because the Order Group is allowed to repeat, an unlimited numbers of vaccinations may be included in a message. Each RXA must be preceded by an ORC.

fields.name: Recorded Date/Time
fields.text: Most systems will default to the system date/time when the transaction was entered, but they should also permit an override.

fields.name: Patient Class
fields.text: This field is used by systems to categorize patients by site.

fields.name: Cyclic Group Maximum Number of Repeats
Error Location
fields.text: Identifies the location in a message related to the identified error, warning or message. Each error will have an ERR, so repeats are not allowed on this field. This field may be left empty if location is not meaningful. For example, if an error involves the entire message (e.g. the message is not parse-able), then location has no meaning. In this case, ERR-2 is left empty.

fields.name: HL7 Error Code
fields.text: Identifies the HL7 (communications) error code.

fields.name: Severity
fields.text: Identifies the severity of an application error. Knowing if something is Error, Warning or Information is intrinsic to how an application handles the content. The Severity code indicates if the system sending the ACK or RSP is reporting an error that caused significant error loss.  This allows the system that initiated the message (VXU or QBP) to alert users that there were issues with the data sent.

fields.name: Application Error Code
fields.text: Application specific code identifying the specific error that occurred.

fields.name: User Message
fields.text: The text message to be displayed to the application user.
